column45: Outcome
column60: Time Incident (Times do not import from dispatch system :(
column110: missionNumber_Debrief (LF#) B-Bangor RW, S-Sanford RW, L-Lewiston RW LG, BG, SG are each ground)
column112: appropriateAsset (Who should have gone if available)
column115: iftRendReferring (If crew met patient somewhere away from the sending hospital, where was that)
column116: sceneIFTReferring (If we were called for a scene call, but it was made an IFT (interfacility) because ambulance brought patient into hospital)
column117: Referring (Free text field used to auto-populate title of entry)
column125: receivingLocationList (picklist used to create receiving name in title
column130: receivedToDispatched_Debrief (Time from call intake to dispatching asset)
column134: transportByPrimaryQ (Did the appropriate asset transport the patient without delay)
column135: preferredGround (met criteria to go by ground based on acuity, distance for response, destination)
column137: reasonL1NoResponse (L1 is Bangor RotorWing, L2 is Lewiston RW, L3 is Bangor FixedWing, L4 is Sanford RW)
column147: ccttResponse (may have been dispatched, but did someone actually respond)
column153: 2ndChartRC (Sometimes we need to document that patient went in both the RW and FW, Previously needed two charts for billing)
column163: abnormalActivationLocationL1 (where was L1 when activated) [KBGR - Bangor airport, KLEW Lewiston Airport, KSFM Sanford airport]
column171: abnormalActivationLocationBCCT (BCCT, SCCT, LCCT is Bangor, Lewiston, or Sanford Ground)
column174: abnormalActivationLocationneoGround (Neo Ground is with NICU team from EMMC - ALWAYS takes longer, I'd consider cohorting in Request Type, column CE)
column176: LF1Weather (What did pilot consider weather when requested, Green is clear blue, Yellow is expect time for me to check it)
column177: l1RespTime (Calculated and often unreliable entry by the Communicator-Dispatcher)
column186: lrrvRespTime (LRRV and SRRV are response SUV's that get crew to patient faster and meet the patient)
column190: reasonL1NoTransport (This is for each time the unit was asked to respond, why couldn't they) FYI - Organizational No Transport reason is column EB and No Air reason is ED)
column197: reasonNEOGNoTransport4 (the 4 at the end is a copying field typo in the API computer code for this field when initially setting up the fields)
column204: refuel (Did helicopter have to stop and get fuel at any time from request to when returning to base)
column206: ifrRequired (Did the pilot fly using Instrument Flight Rules on this operation)
column208: rwInDarkness (Any part of call done in darkness)
column213: MixedMileageFW (If RW and FW were used for one patient transport)
column215: requestToResponseMins (Organization response time, very, very unreliable accuracy and likely unusable due to manual calculation and entry, and well, some humans make more or less errors than others, or use the wrong times for when transport request was first entered)
column216: responseDelay (Subjective and with no objective time for them to decide, none or select reason, just gustalt)
column218: unscheduledPassengerFW (Did someone other than crew go in FW transport from sending facility)
column221: passengerFormFW (was safety and emergency/info form sent to dispatch)
column226: acsTaskSaturationWorkload (What extraordinary things happened to Communicator during the course of this transport request)
column239: criteria (depracated field after summer of 24ish, did the patient criteria meet objective acuity for transport by a critical care team)
column240: bed (was a bed available at the receiving at time of transport request) [you have no idea how often we get asked to come get a patient when there is no place for us to take them, but because there are times we need to go and help the sending facility, these questions were asked
column241: expertise2 (Did they say "yes, we need you, when no bed available")
column242: adminForNoBed (If didn't meet criteria, who said we could go anyways)
column248: receivingRendezvous (Did an ambulance meet us and take the patient from us at the airport to the receiving? Hardly ever, like close to never happens)
